	<tr>
		<td bgcolor="#DEDACB">
	
			<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
			I can only assume that there are a whole LOT of people out there that have absolutely no idea how to play a wizard.  This class, folks, is about strategy.  Not damage ratios, not whoopin' ass, but strategy.  This spell, Column of Frost, is quite possibly the most useful spell I've purchased to date.  Solo, it's useless.  Well, DUH!  It's an AoE spell.  However, in a group...   Last night, I ventured with two 7th level tanks into the bowels of Blackburrow.  Mostly, I just let the tanks aggro the mobs, then I sparingly use a few flame bursts and maybe a Shock of Ice.  Admittedly, I'm not contributing as much damage in an even fight as the tanks are doing.  However, we later ran into three mid blues and a white.  First, I let the tanks get the white good and mad.  Then, waited until the others had bashed on the tanks a bit, (hey-- they're tanks. In a fight they lose health, I lose mana.  Thatsa the way it works).  Once they were both down to about 2/3 health and had beat on more than one of the gnolls, I cast Okeil's on both of them.  This served to get the mobs even madder at them.  Still no gnolls are coming for me.  Finally, I cast CoF *directly on* the burly (white) gnoll.  He dies, another gnoll is hit and runs, and two are left, both hit by CoF.  I SoI one; he dies.  I flame burst the runner-- he dies.  The tanks finish off the last one.<BR>
<BR>
Later on, I tried many different variations on using CoF/Okeil's/SoI.  In all instances I cast directly on a mob in a tight group with CoF.  Only ONCE did I have a gnoll break off and attack me personally.<BR>
<BR>
LEARN HOW TO USE YOUR SPELLS, folks.  I see lot of people whining about how everything but the single-target DD spells are just aggro-magnets; that simply ain't true.  You're just not using the spell correctly.  The tanks may not understand why you don't start nuking in an even fight, but the first time you help pull out a battle like the one above, they'll stop questioning your tactics, I guarantee it.  They may be grunts, but they know they can't defeat three risky blues and a white on their own; and when they see 'em go down like I described above, they KNOW who was doing the real damage, there.<BR>
<BR>
Yes, there are times when a mob is gonna get a wild hair and come after YOU.  It happens; deal with it.  But, you can minimize it to an acceptable risk with proper tactics and thinking about what spell is appropiate to memorize for where you're fighting.  A properly played wizard IS still the single most powerful character in the game when grouped, I assure you.  But, you  have to know HOW to play the role.  If you play it like a fighter with flashy-light thingees, you'll die.  If you play it like a druid, you'll die.  Play like a wizard, use that high IQ, and stop whining about this spell or that spell being useless and an aggro-magnet.  CoF is a GREAT spell for 8th level, you just have to know when and how to use it.<BR>
<BR>
*rant off* :)
			</font>
	
		</td>
	</tr>
	
